04353nam a22006255i 9781477306161DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211991txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773061617 a10.7560/7114022doi  a(DE-B1597)587047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a972.83/111 aJoyce, Rosemary A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCerro Palenque :bPower and Identity on the Maya Periphery /cRosemary A. Joyce. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1991  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Archaeological Background -- tChapter 3. Research at Cerro Palenque -- tChapter 4. Social and Political Structure -- tChapter 5. Social Dynamics: Interaction -- tChapter 6. Social Dynamics: Transformation -- tChapter 7. An Interpretive Archaeography -- tReferences Cited -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExcavations at Cerro Palenque, a hilltop site in the Ulua Valley of northwest Honduras, revolutionized scholars’ ideas about the Terminal Classic period (roughly ad 850–1050) of Maya history and about the way in which cultures of the southeast Maya periphery related to the Lowland Maya. In this pathfinding study, Rosemary Joyce combines archaeological data gleaned from site research in 1980–1983 with anthropological theory about the evolution of social power to reconstruct something of the culture and lifeways of the prehispanic inhabitants of Cerro Palenque. Joyce organizes her study in a novel way. Rather than presenting each category of excavated material (ceramics, lithics, etc.) in a separate chapter, she integrates this data in discussions of what people did and where they did it, resulting in a reconstruction of social activity more than in a description of material culture. Joyce’s findings indicate that the precolumbian elites of the Ulua Valley had very strong and diversified contacts with Lowland Maya culture, primarily through the Bay of Honduras, with far less contact with Copán in the Highlands. The elites used their contacts with these distant, powerful cultures to reinforce their difference from the people they ruled and the legitimacy of their privileged status. Indeed, their dependence on foreign contacts ultimately led to their downfall when their foreign partners reorganized their economic and social order during the Terminal Classic period. Although archaeological research in the region has been undertaken since the 1890s, Cerro Palenque is the first full-length study of an Ulua Valley site ever published. Joyce’s pioneering approach—archaeological ethnography—will be of interest to scholars dealing with any prehistoric people whose material remains provide the only clues to their culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCerro Palenque Site (Honduras). 0aMayas-Antiquities. 0aMayas-Social life and customs. 0aSocial archaeology-Honduras. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477306161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477306161/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK